Throughout Bolivia, which is a landlocked country, the memory of the coastline lost in Chile ' s favour as a result of the bloody conflict of the 19th century over resources is still alive; the desire to navigate the Pacific Ocean again is alive and alive.
Those hopes may have been the most bold in recent decades, as Bolivia awaits the decision of an international court to be held on 1 October as a result of five years of debate.
“Bolivia has energy, a spirit of unity and a balance of mind, and of course there is a positive outcome,” said Bolivia’s diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians will observe the high-screening of the International Court of Justice throughout the country, hoping that the Tribunal in The Hague will be able to support Bolivia ' s statement that, after decades of intense negotiations, Chile has a duty to negotiate for Bolivia ' s sovereign access to the sea.
