John Edward: Languages are of great importance to the citizens of the world
The Scottish independent schools continue their tradition of brilliant education, as confirmed again in 2018: outstanding examinations have demonstrated individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other socially important disciplines.
These schools belong to the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), where more than 30,000 pupils are enrolled throughout Scotland, and seek to provide the highest level of services for pupils and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their pupils for further higher education, career choices and status as citizens of the world.
As part of the education sector, which is responsible for the design and implementation of the individual school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and desirable in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you call upon his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, you speak to his heart.”
This is a convincing indication that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships with and trust the citizens of other countries.
From the latest examinations of this year, we see that languages are in the leading positions in the league tables and have the highest scores in the independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of foreign-language students received the highest A rating.
Data from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 per cent of pupils received “A” in Mandarin (Chinese language), while 72 per cent of students in German, 69 per cent in French and 63 per cent in Spanish also received “A”.
This proves that in independent schools in Scotland, foreign languages are clearly considered vital for children and young people in the future.
Language subjects now enjoy the same demand as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other educational institutions.
A survey conducted by the British Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that 17 per cent of the reasons that made it difficult for employers to fill vacancies were a lack of language skills.
Language skills are thus increasingly becoming the key to a successful future career for young people.
Given that more promising jobs require language skills, these skills are needed in a globalized world.
No matter what kind of profession a student chooses if he learns a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future by acquiring another additional skill that he will benefit from throughout his life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows several foreign languages a competitive advantage.
According to a YouTube survey involving over 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak the foreign language well enough to support the conversation, and French was the only language with two digits — 15 percent of respondents spoke it.
That is why investing in language education is so relevant now.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of countries with emerging economies, would give children a better chance of finding a good job.
There is a wide variety of languages in Scotland’s schools that are taught — each school has its own set of languages.
A number of schools focus on more classic modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be the most important to Britain in the light of the future development of the country before 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of your child, in independent schools there will always be a choice of several languages with teaching staff whose members are specialists in these languages.
Independent schools in Scotland seek to create an educational environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, regardless of their future.
At present, it cannot be denied that languages remain vital to the future development of the country in the global business environment and should therefore be appropriately reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages really need to be seen as “the skills of international communication”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, providing diversity and benefits for young people in Scotland.
Il faunt byen le fire.
John Edwards, Director, Board of Independent Schools of Scotland
