Harvard students learn to rest in special courses
The new course introduced this year at Harvard University helped all elementary students to learn to sleep more and to fight the chauvinist culture of uninterrupted caffeine consumption to keep awake “nights through.”
One of the academics found that the world’s most successful students often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chaisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital Clinic, developed a course that he considered to be the first in the United States.
After his discovery, he was aroused by the idea of introducing such a course, giving a preliminary report on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning processes.
"At the end of my presentation, a girl came to me and said, 'I'm sorry I only found out now that I'm about to finish my studies.'
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first offered to students this year, shows how healthy sleep habits contribute to academic and sports achievement, and how it improves the general health of the individual.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Executive Director of the University's Health Service, said that the university had decided to introduce the course after it had been determined that students had serious sleep deficiencies during the school week.
It lasts one hour, and the students perform a number of interactive tasks.
One section of the class offers an image of a dorm room where students, by clicking on coffee cups, curtains, gymnasiums, and books, learn how each of these actions and substances — coffee, light, which causes a lack of sleep — affect sports results and how important it is to get enough sleep every day.
In another section, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
An interactive campus map encourages participants to think about their daily lives.
“We understand that these classes will not change the behaviour of the students at once.
But we believe that they have a right to know, like any other person has a right to know, for example, how smoking affects his health,” Professor Chaseler added.
He said that a false sense of pride for being able to “smell all night” is still quite common, and modern technology, as well as increasing pressure on students, means that sleep deprivation is becoming a problem.
According to him, enough sleep of good quality is the student's “secret weapon” to deal with stress, nervous exhaustion and anxiety, and even to deal with overweight, because under-slapping puts the brain in a mode of hunger, making it constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian researcher in chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaisler develop a course by attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and inspired him to disseminate this information throughout the campus.
He hoped that the next step would be to ask all postgraduate students to take a similar curriculum before entering a competitive educational institution.
Professor Chaisler recommends that students set up an alarm to warn them that they should go to bed and wake up, and that they should remember the harmful effects of the “blue light” produced by electronic screens and LED lamps, which disrupt human bioritm and lead to problems of sleep.
