The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new Internet for Google and Facebook.
Tim Berners-Lee, an inventor of the World Wide Web, launches a startup that claims to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company based on an open Berners-Lee Solid platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people to access what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company Berners-Lee, it was a joke that the goal of Inrupt was to gain “peaceful domination.”
“We must do it now,” he says about his startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The application uses the Solid technology, which allows people to create their own "personal online data warehouses" or POD.
It may contain lists of contacts, cases, as well as a calendar, a music library and other personal and professional data tools.
The application is based on the same principle as Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify, all of which can be used in the same browser and at the same time.
The uniqueness of the personal online data repository is that it is fully managed by the user, who can access any necessary information.
The company calls this principle “personal empowerment through data”.
According to the CEO of John Bruce, the Inrupt idea was that the company provided resources, processes and appropriate skills to make Solid accessible to all.
The company is now composed of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a number of staff developers contracted to work on the project, and a volunteer programmer community.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team were not negotiating with Facebook and Google about whether or not his companies should make radical changes that would change all their business models overnight.
“We do not ask them for permission.”
In his post on Medium, published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "the Inrupt mission is to provide commercial energy and ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid".
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by creating a World Wide Web consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee's voice has been quite influential in the debate about online neutrality.
Even by launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Internet Foundation, and the Open Data Institute.
“I am incredibly optimistic about this next era of the Internet,” says Berners-Lee.
