National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
A new study carried out in one of the Scottish hills is designed to show how bats use the landscape to find food.
It is hoped that the data will provide a new insight into the behaviour of unique winged mammals and help to further preserve species.
A study organized by the National Foundation of Scotland will examine common non-topys, sopranos, and brown long-haired bats and Dobanton nights, inhabited by Inverewe Gardens, West Ross.
Special recorders will be installed at some locations around the site to track bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile site surveys using manual detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all records will determine the frequency of screams and the activities for which different groups of these animals are responsible.
A habitat map will then be drawn up and a report prepared to provide a detailed picture of their landscape-wide behaviour.
Rob Dewar, the NTS Nature Conservation Adviser, hopes that these results will show which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the main areas of habitat management, such as grassland formation, as well as how to maintain forest areas in a state optimal for bats and other associated species.
The population of bats in Scotland and throughout Britain has declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened with extinction due to construction and development work that affects their habitat and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can be dangerous, as well as adhesive fly ribbons, chemical processing of building materials and hunting of domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, their night hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They're using sophisticated echo equipment to pinpoint the obstacles on their way to flight.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes the issue of the bat population very seriously.
The organization has 10 trained experts who conduct regular interviews, field checks and sometimes rescue work.
The organization has even created the first and only reserve of bats in Scotland at Threave Mansion in Damfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten species of Scottish bats live.
The real estate manager, David Thompson, says the estate is the perfect place for them.
"Here, in Threave, a great place for bats," he says.
"There are old buildings here, many old trees and all the elements of a good environment.
But much about bats remains unknown, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us to better understand what they need to live well.”
It recalls the importance of testing the presence of bats prior to maintenance within private domains, as the unintentional destruction of one nest could lead to the death of up to 400 females and young persons, and possibly even to the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected by law, their destruction, harassment or destruction of their habitats is illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer of the bat conservation fund, appeals to the public for help.
She says, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don't know how many of their individual species live."
