She went on to say, "I was very helpful to a woman who worked in a management position somewhere, and she told me that she also cried when she was angry, but she developed a technique that she used to explain to her interlocutor, "You may think I'm crying because I'm upset.
I'm really angry."
And then she just kept talking.
I was very impressed with this approach.”
Tears are allowed as an exit to anger, partly because they are fundamentally misinterpreted.
One of my most painful memories of my first job in an office dominated by men: one day I cried out of furious anger, but I was grabbed by an elderly woman, a soulless manager, who I was always afraid of, and dragged into a stairwell.
“Never let them see you crying,” she said to me.
“They don't know you're crying out of anger.
They think you're upset, and they're happy to think that you've finally got mad at you."
