How a trade war with America can benefit Beijing
Experts believe that the first spikes of the US-China trade war were stunning, and while the battle is far from over, the division between countries can benefit Beijing in the long run.
Donald Trump, President of the United States, issued his first warning earlier this year, taxing key Chinese exports, including solar batteries, steel, and aluminium.
The most significant escalation occurred this week, when new tariffs affected products worth $200 billion (150 billion pounds), effectively taxing half of all goods coming to the US from China.
Beijing has been retaliating each time, recently imposing duties on United States goods at a cost of $60 billion, ranging from five to ten per cent.
China promised that the response to the US would be equal every time, and the world’s second largest economy is unlikely to start to experience at least the slightest difficulties in the near future.
Making Washington retreat means giving in to demands, but publicly giving in to the US would be too shameful for Xi Jinping, China’s president.
Nevertheless, experts believe that if Beijing can play its cards correctly, the US trade war pressure can provide long-term support to China by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision in Washington or Beijing can create conditions that will lead to economic corking in any of these countries is, in fact, far more dangerous than previously acknowledged by observers,” says Abigail Grace, a researcher at the Center for New American Security, which specializes in Asia.
The Minister for Foreign Affairs stated that Syria was “prepared” for the return of refugees
Syria stated that it was ready for the voluntary return of refugees and was seeking assistance in rebuilding a country devastated by a war that had lasted more than seven years.
Addressing the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid Al-Mualem reported that conditions were improving.
“The situation on the ground today has become more stable and secure because of the success of the fight against terrorism”, he said.
The Government continues to rebuild areas destroyed by terrorists so that people can live in peace there.
At present, all conditions are in place for the voluntary return of refugees to a country that they have had to leave because of terrorist attacks and unilateral economic measures that have affected their daily lives.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the outbreak of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Mu'alem said that the Syrian regime would be grateful for helping to rebuild the destroyed country.
But he stressed that the country would not accept assistance on any terms or from countries sponsoring terrorism.
